<poster>
<seg id="2"> yun feiquan </seg>
</poster>
<seg id="3"> dell inc. (us; dell) and google confirmed on tuesday that dell is testing personal computers loaded with google's software packages. </seg>
<seg id="4"> this move might pose a serious threat to the dominant status of microsoft corp., msft, in the pc software market. </seg>
<seg id="5"> jess blackburn, the news spokesman for dell corporation, said that the corporation is assessing google's software. </seg>
<seg id="6"> after the software is installed, pc users can use the software to search not only on the internet, but also for information stored on their pcs. </seg>
<seg id="7"> blackburn confirmed that the software the corporation is testing includes the dell homepage supported by google, google's desktop search system and google's toolbar. </seg>
<seg id="8"> google's news spokesman, jon murchinson, also confirmed at the same time that his company is testing a batch of software, developed by google, with dell. </seg>
<seg id="9"> as the wall street journal previously reported, google - the it new baron - is negotiating with dell and hewlett-packard co., and is trying to persuade these computer manufacturing giants to install google's software for their computers. </seg>
<seg id="10"> according to an internal source cited by the wall street journal, to achieve the goal, google might pay 1 billion dollars to dell in the coming three years. </seg>
<seg id="11"> however, neither company has disclosed related details. </seg>
<seg id="12"> and also, the hewlett-packard side has refused to make a comment on it. </seg>
<seg id="13"> the microsoft corporation news spokesman, neil charney, refused to make a comment on the news mentioned above. </seg>
<seg id="14"> microsoft is currently planning to promote its next-generation search tool for the windows operating system and strengthen development of its online business. </seg>
<seg id="15"> on the day the news was released, google's stock price fell another 4.46%, dropping to 367.92 dollars. </seg>
<seg id="16"> the microsoft's stock price fell 1%, and closed at 26.94 dollars on that day. </seg>
<seg id="17"> some analysts pointed out that google is anxious to seek another direction of expansion in addition to network searches, and that its integration with dell and other pc giants might prompt google to threaten microsoft's core business. </seg>
<seg id="18"> matt rosoff, an analyst on microsoft's direction at a market investigation and research company, said that microsoft is absolutely concerned and worried that google is eager to expand its new income sources. </seg>
<seg id="19"> but some analysts do not think so. </seg>
<seg id="20"> charles di bona, an analyst at market analysis company sanford c. bernstein, pointed out that it is too early for google to shake microsoft's dominant status. </seg>
<seg id="21"> reporter's journal: google shakes microsoft's domination? </seg>
<seg id="22"> hui zhengyi </seg>
<seg id="23"> there is no doubt that computers have become necessities in the life and work of modern people. </seg>
<seg id="24"> however, there is only a minority of people who understand the working rationale of computers, when everyone can skillfully operate them. </seg>
<seg id="25"> like they use "dummy" cameras, most "newbies" can play the black boxes well as long as those boxes have friendly interfaces, and convenient and simple software. </seg>
<seg id="26"> thus, original software installed on a pc manufacturer's products can usually determine most consumers' using habits. </seg>
<seg id="27"> it is through this measure that microsoft has tightly controlled the pc operating system market. </seg>
<seg id="28"> right now, google, a new rival of microsoft, tends to share part of the market through the same measure. </seg>
<seg id="29"> a well-known economics medium in taiwan recently made a very interesting metaphor. </seg>
<seg id="30"> "computer manufacturers including dell and hewlett-packard are starting to use computers like shelves in a supermarket and are collecting the "stocking fee" from software companies. </seg>
<seg id="31"> a successful bidder can make its own software show up in the 'critical ten minutes' when users turn on their new computers, and guide consumers to use its products. </seg>
<seg id="32"> this kind of fee collection mode is like how a supermarket collects stocking fees from food manufacturers. </seg>
<seg id="33"> this phenomenon demonstrates that microsoft's control power is beginning to loosen without a doubt. </seg>
<seg id="34"> managers at microsoft have warned bill gates that the microsoft's hegemonic status will eventually be threatened if google starts to pay pc manufacturers for installation of google's software on their computer products. </seg>
<seg id="35"> no matter what the outcome is, the number one status that microsoft has been enjoying in those comfortable days may become history. </seg>
<seg id="36"> after all, it is easy to become dominant, but it is difficult to maintain a dominant status. </seg>
