<DOC docid="groups.google.com_greenpartycn_b07aeae684cbc1b7_CMN_20060209_051800" genre="newsgroup" sysid="chg">
<hl>
<seg id="1"> negotiation and compromise are the important means of democracy! (zt) </seg>
</hl>
<poster>
<seg id="2"> houze </seg>
</poster>
<seg id="3"> i just now saw a poster on "great decency -to old mr. guiren" sent by a network friend. </seg>
<seg id="4"> his (her) original words are that "negotiation and compromise are the important means of democracy. otherwise, a split because of different views is a failure of democracy!!! hope that those ideal democrats pay fully attention to this!" </seg>
<seg id="5"> this plain and tasteless sentence, which has not attracted interest from any network friends, has made me imagine a lot and have many sorts of feelings. </seg>
<seg id="6"> at that moment i thought of the ancient times of china and the past of the west. </seg>
<seg id="7"> i seldom sent the main poster. i cannot help but reply to the poster of the network friend in the way of the main poster. </seg>
<seg id="8"> let's see china's ancient times. </seg>
<seg id="9"> everyone knows that since qin shihuang established the universally unified and centralized power system in china, any subsequent dynasties were operated under the political framework. </seg>
<seg id="10"> although the han dynasty temporarily implemented a "two-track system," i.e. a political system that practiced the feudal system and centralized power system at the same time, it eventually switched to a complete centralized power system in the end. </seg>
<seg id="11"> the outcome of this kind of centralized power system had an advanced aspect in the historical condition by then, which promoted the development of productivity. </seg>
<seg id="12"> but we should also see that the long-term operation of the system for more than 2,000 years had made local administrations lacking of their creativities, initiatives, and enthusiasms, and unable to make various suitable systems and policies for local developments based on local circumstances. </seg>
<seg id="13"> the pyramid type of ruling system had made lower-class officials looking upward only and following directions from their superiors for everything. </seg>
<seg id="14"> there was no room for coordination and negotiation because even local officials at the county level were appointed by the central government, not to mention those common people. </seg>
<seg id="15"> when rights of farmers were infringed upon in ancient china, they could only bear it time and again. </seg>
<seg id="16"> only when their basest rights were threatened, i.e. when a famine spread in big areas, a tyrannical rule or natural disaster caused loss of their living rights, would they rebel. </seg>
<seg id="17"> in more than 2,000 years, many peasant uprisings spread everywhere in the country like storms, but they never won a victory in a real sense except zhu yuanzhang, from chen sheng, and wu guang, who did not plan their uprising to the planned huang jin insurrection, from the huang chao revolt in the tang dynasty to the li zhicheng rebellion that established a dynasty for only a month. </seg>
<seg id="18"> even the ming dynasty created by zhu yuanzhang was only a cycle of other dynasties, and there were no systematic changes. </seg>
<seg id="19"> zhu yuanzhang, who came from a common family and did not receive much education, played the chinese ancient centralized power system to a sick extent, and to extremes. since then, the vigorous state of the type of the tang dynasty that was open, free, and tolerant, had become depressed. </seg>
<seg id="20"> the atmosphere of freedom of speech disappeared in the vast land of china for a time. </seg>
<seg id="21"> human nature was suppressed to the maximum extent. </seg>
<seg id="22"> everybody became very cautious and dared not to say more words with reverence and awe. </seg>
<seg id="23"> this was the only outcome of peasant uprisings in 2,000 years, and it made chinese people neither humans nor ghosts. </seg>
<seg id="24"> let's see the medieval ages of the so-called dark time in western europe. </seg>
<seg id="25"> the medieval ages of western europe were formed after the western rome was destroyed by nomadic nations, and lasted for a thousand years. they had nothing to do with the ancient greece and rome of the past. </seg>
<seg id="26"> those ages featured the feudal system, i.e. land holding. </seg>
<seg id="27"> many layers of land feudal lords, from the top to the bottom, had more autonomy. </seg>
<seg id="28"> no matter whether small feudal lords who had an area of several square kilometers, or nobles who had titles of duke, marquis, count, viscount, and baron, since superiors and inferiors, and the left and right, could balance, restrain, and were interdependent with each other, and had their prerequisites and capabilities to strive for their own rights against kings, the scenes in which nobles sat with a king negotiating for their own interest emerged, which never happened in china's ancient times. </seg>
<seg id="29"> compromises and concessions were made mutually instead use of violent means to knock down or replace opponents. </seg>
<seg id="30"> in this way, through making various contracts, rights were continuously transferred to nobles and common people, and they had more and more rights, and kings had fewer and fewer. </seg>
<seg id="31"> later, the british queen had only a status for display, and not any substantial power. </seg>
<seg id="32"> democracy was gradually realized in this way! </seg>
<seg id="33"> let's come back again to compare with ancient china, where every power was concentrated in the hands of emperors (except li shimin), and there were almost no nobles. it was very difficult for peasants to be able to sit in front of a negotiation table, joyfully making compromises and concessions on a contract agreed to by both sides while enjoying a cup of tea or a glass of wine. </seg>
<seg id="34"> under this circumstance, when the living right was taken away, only violent means could overthrow an existing dynasty and try to replace it. </seg>
<seg id="35"> its outcome was the repeated cycle from the peak of the tang dynasty to the sick status of the ming dynasty. </seg>
<seg id="36"> comparing histories between china and the west, we discovered that the contradictions between rulers and the ruled in ancient china were much more intensified than those in ancient western countries. </seg>
<seg id="37"> no western countries had so many continuous peasant uprisings as ancient china had. </seg>
<seg id="38"> in the western countries, when differences between ancient royal families and peasants emerged, what nobles and common people thought of first was to settle them through a negotiation path, to obtain more rights gradually by making mutual concessions, and they seldom used violent means. </seg>
<seg id="39"> understanding this, when we enter into the 21st century, we can still see those democratic warriors in networks who have inherited the ideology of the absolute power concentration system of the ming dynasty, </seg>
<seg id="40"> and have been poisoned by the virus of the cultural revolution that they can say nothing except those words of "down with or overthrow something." </seg>
<seg id="41"> and those concepts are the biggest barrier to democracy, because those people do not understand that negotiation, coordination, and compromise are the most important means and path for realization of democracy. </seg>
</DOC>
<DOC docid="groups.google.com_greenpartycn_b1314fab782e7592_CMN_20060209_044700" genre="newsgroup" sysid="chg">
<hl>
<seg id="1"> cao xiaoming: who is going to "pay the bill" for enriching cultural activities in rural areas </seg>
</hl>
<poster>
<seg id="2"> hou ze </seg>
</poster>
<seg id="3"> the author was lucky to spend this year's spring festival in a rural area of the mainland, and visited some relatives and friends. </seg>
<seg id="4"> i was not only influenced by the dense atmosphere of the festival in the chinese rural area, but also concerned about those boring cultural activities there. </seg>
<seg id="5"> the author discovered in a village where my relatives lived that this village organized villagers spontaneously to play a drama called "trotting horse lamp" for every spring festival in the past. </seg>
<seg id="6"> the drama is based on figures in the story of the three kingdoms. any adult or child could play a role in the drama, and villagers were not bored at all to watch it a hundred times. </seg>
<seg id="7"> there were several of this kind of performance teams of "trotting horse lamp" in the whole township. they performed not only in their own villages, but also went to other villages for visits, and exchanged frequently. </seg>
<seg id="8"> but this village did not organize the performance this year. </seg>
<seg id="9"> the reason is that just the costumes for "trotting horse lamp" would cost a lot, which were bought in the past through donations from villagers. now they are too worn out to be taken on. </seg>
<seg id="10"> nobody was willing to donate any more, if asking villagers for donations household by household. other villages in the township had a similar situation. </seg>
<seg id="11"> the village suddenly became quiet without the "trotting horse lamp." </seg>
<seg id="12"> adults started to play mahjong. </seg>
<seg id="13"> children also began to play cards. </seg>
<seg id="14"> villagers said that this festival had no fun. </seg>
<seg id="15"> the big scene in the countryside is either shooting off fireworks or playing mahjong during the festival. </seg>
<seg id="16"> the gambling trend cannot be stopped even though it is prohibited time and again, and is spread even further. gambling for up to ten thousand yuan has become a routine game. especially, big batches of those migrant farmer workers who come back to their hometowns from other areas have played major roles in gambling sites. </seg>
<seg id="17"> their hard-earned money from working in other areas for a year is lost in this way. </seg>
<seg id="18"> family disputes occurred time and again because of gambling, which sometimes causes tragedies with families broken up and decimated. </seg>
<seg id="19"> some farmers said that they gambled not only during festivals but also participated in gambling frequently in slack seasons. </seg>
<seg id="20"> nowhere to go if they did not gamble. </seg>
<seg id="21"> it is too difficult to organize cultural activities and look for "fun" in the countryside. </seg>
<seg id="22"> not only are there no facilities and funding, but also nobody organizes them. </seg>
<seg id="23"> but in this aspect, the practice in jiangxi is definitely good news for farmers. </seg>
<seg id="24"> to enrich the cultural life of the farmer masses, the government of jiangxi province not only implemented the policy that "the government provides funding for it; the market operates it; townships build stages; and farmers watch dramas" last september, </seg>
<seg id="25"> but they also arranged at least 60 million yuan every year for the special fund for rural cultural causes and delivered good-quality cultural products to the rural masses. </seg>
<seg id="26"> in the beginning of this new year, it added an additional 40 million yuan, a total of 100 million yuan, for the establishment of special funding for the rural cultural cause. </seg>
<seg id="27"> and also, what this special funding "paid" toward the farmers' "bill" is quite a good deal: </seg>
<seg id="28"> various professional performance organizations are invited to have shows in rural areas, and provide at least four shows for every town each year. </seg>
<seg id="29"> movie companies at every level are invited to organize film projection teams to show movies in the countryside, and at least six feature or scientific education movies should be shown for every administrative village each year; </seg>
