<hl>
<seg id="1"> <headline> military observation: how long can iran hold out under us air attacks? </seg>
</hl>
<poster>
<seg id="2"> <poster>  yun feiquan </seg>
</poster>
<seg id="3"> if we describe conventional war of attrition as causing the opponent to bleed to death, then from the outset modern warfare consists of shooting a gun toward the opponent's head in order to render him a "vegetable" even before there is time to bleed. </seg>
<seg id="4"> the disparity between the military capabilities of iran and the us is not one of quantity, but rather in the understanding of modern war. </seg>
<seg id="5"> iran, which fought a victorless eight-year war with iraq, seems not yet to have understood the true significance of modern hi-tech warfare. </seg>
<seg id="6"> following an analysis of us military deployments, britain's "international intelligence--commentary" recently said that the us military is carrying out preparations to launch a large scale air assault on iran...... </seg>
<seg id="7"> the current status of iran's air force is cause for concern. </seg>
<seg id="8"> the present situation of iran's air force is quite similar to that of iraq's air force prior to the 2003 war. </seg>
<seg id="9"> the country does not possess the capacity to research and develop modern weapons on its own and is also under an arms embargo imposed by the west. </seg>
<seg id="10"> once war breaks out, it is uncertain whether the antiquated planes in iran's air force will be able to take to the air to engage us forces. </seg>
<seg id="11"> at present, iran's air-defense system consists primarily of an air force belonging to iran's regular forces, the land-based air-defense force and the air-defense capacity of the revolutionary guard. </seg>
<seg id="12"> of these, iran's air force presently has a manpower of 50,000 and more than 300 aircraft of various models. </seg>
<seg id="13"> the most important aircraft models include us-manufactured f-4 phantoms, f5 tigers, f-14 tomcats and russian-manufactured mig-29s. </seg>
<seg id="14"> the land-based air-defense force is primarily equipped with surface-to-air missiles of the us-manufactured hawk series and the british rapier series, as well as a portion belong to the russian-manufactured sam series. </seg>
<seg id="15"> with regards to the current status of iran's air-defense strength,  analysis by individuals such as the us military expert harold hutchison and  military expert [hela muqixin] of the [russian political and military research institute] indicates that, viewed from the present situation, there are still holes in iran's air-defense capabilities and air-defense system. </seg>
<seg id="16"> hutchison says that with respect to overall capabilities, iran's air force simply is not on the same level as the us air force. </seg>
<seg id="17"> a large number of the us-manufactured jetfighters that iran is equipped with cannot be used because of a lack of spare parts and upgrading. </seg>
<seg id="18"> the f-14 fighter was once the trump card of iran's air force, but today there are only ten or so that are able to fly. </seg>
<seg id="19"> the dependability in actual combat of the aim-54 phoenix missiles they carry, known for their ultra-long distance attack capabilities, is also doubtful. </seg>
<seg id="20"> [hela muqixin] points out however that the air-defense missile systems provided to iran by the us in the 1970s and 1980s have lost their warfare capabilities because of a lack of spare parts. </seg>
<seg id="21"> in addition, the other non-systematic air-defense weapons obtained from russia and other countries are simply incapable of countering us forces possessing powerful electromagnetic countermeasure capabilities. </seg>
<seg id="22"> scraping together a military affects battle capability </seg>
<seg id="23"> clearly, iran's government is also aware that its fate in a conflict depends upon whether it can defend the sky above and it has been carrying out eleventh-hour preparations by scraping together whatever it can find in order to build up its air-defense system. </seg>
<seg id="24"> at present, its methods can be summarized into two devices: </seg>
<seg id="25"> the first is an all-out effort to conceal key nuclear facilities and beef up their defense capabilities. </seg>
<seg id="26"> according to a report in the british newspaper the times, iran has hidden the natanz nuclear facility, the isfahan uranium enrichment center and other core components of their nuclear facilities eighteen meters underground and added a two-meter thick concrete protection shell. </seg>
<seg id="27"> but the us military is one step ahead. as early as the 1991 persian gulf war, it saw the effectiveness of underground bunkers in anti-aircraft defense and rushed to develop various types of earth-penetrating bombs. </seg>
<seg id="28"> after ten years of focused research, the us military has a full complement of strategies and weapons to counter reinforced underground bunkers. </seg>
<seg id="29"> iran has recently also bought a large amount of advanced air-defense weapons from russia. </seg>
<seg id="30"> since the end of last year, iran's government has reached a series of agreements with russia to purchase pechora-2a air defense missile systems as well as 29 tor-m1 air-defense missile systems valued at us$700m. </seg>
<seg id="31"> however, modern warfare is a contest of system against system. </seg>
<seg id="32"> the various air-attack weapons of the us military have all been developed by the country itself for its own benefit and, through many years of perfectioning in actual combat, they have been molded into an impressive war machine. </seg>
<seg id="33"> on the other hand, iran's "up-to-date weapons" have been scraped together from other countries. whether or not they can be made combat effective in such a short time is still in question. </seg>
<seg id="34"> iran's lags behind not only in weapons </seg>
<seg id="35"> the concept of "air-land battle" was first raised in "operations", published by the us military in 1982. it stresses reliance on strength in the air to carry out attacks against the enemy's strategically valuable targets. this paralyses the other side's command systems at the start of the war and turns the enemy's conventional forces, even if they are superior, into a "slab of meat on a cutting board." </seg>
<seg id="36"> in the 1991 persian gulf war, the 1999 kosovo war and the 2003 iraq war, the us military did not concern itself with how many planes the opponent had, but rather the range of its own tomahawk cruise missiles. </seg>
<seg id="37"> even if iran's government has prepared for a possible air attack and has begun to take steps to reinforce its air-defense capabilities, iran, which fought to a stalemate in an eight-year war with iraq, seems not to have fully understood the true meaning of modern hi-tech warfare. </seg>
<seg id="38"> with the progress of the us military's military transformation in recent years, the us military's air-attack operations are completely different from the carpet bombing of the vietnam war and instead rely on full-depth air assaults with various hi-tech weapons and modern information technology. </seg>
<seg id="39"> faced with this kind of air assault, how long iran's land-based air defense systems can hold out is an unknown. </seg>
<seg id="40"> source: cri online- "world news journal" </seg>
