<hl>
<seg id="1"> <headline> joining hands with google to battle microsoft: will dell charge microsoft "top-shelf fees"? </seg>
</hl>
<poster>
<seg id="2"> <poster>  yun feiquan </seg>
</poster>
<seg id="3"> dell inc. (us: dell) and google confirmed on tuesday that dell is currently testing pcs installed with google's software pack. </seg>
<seg id="4"> this step could form a significant threat to microsoft's (microsoftcorp., msft) dominant position in the pc software market. </seg>
<seg id="5"> dell spokesman jess blackburn said the company is currently evaluating google's software. </seg>
<seg id="6"> after the software has been installed, the pc-user will be able to use the software to conduct searches on the internet as well as search through information stored on the pc. </seg>
<seg id="7"> blackburn confirmed that the software being evaluated by the company includes a google-supported dell homepage, a google desktop search tool and a google tool bar. </seg>
<seg id="8"> at the same time, google spokesman jon murchinson also confirmed that the company was working with dell in testing a software bundle developed by google. </seg>
<seg id="9"> earlier, a report in the wall street journal had said that it upstart google was in talks with dell and hewlett-packard in an attempt to convince the computer manufacturing giants to install google software in their computers. </seg>
<seg id="10"> according to an insider quoted by the wall street journal, in order to achieve this end, google may have to pay up to us$3bn over the next three years. </seg>
<seg id="11"> however, the two companies have not disclosed any relevant details. </seg>
<seg id="12"> furthermore, hp still refuses to issue a comment. </seg>
<seg id="13"> microsoft spokesman neil charney refused to comment on the above information. </seg>
<seg id="14"> currently, microsoft is planning to launch a search tool for the next generation of its windows operating system and strengthen the development of its online business. </seg>
<seg id="15"> on the day of the news statement, shares in google fell another 4.46% to us$367.92. </seg>
<seg id="16"> shares in microsoft fell that day by 1% to close at us$26.94. </seg>
<seg id="17"> some analysts say that google is eagerly seeking to expand in a direction beyond web searching and that linking up with dell and other pc giants could prompt google to threaten microsoft in its core businesses. </seg>
<seg id="18"> matt rosoff, analyst with the market research firm directions on microsoft, says that microsoft is unquestionably concerned and worried by google's eagerness to expand into other sources of revenue. </seg>
<seg id="19"> but other analysts strongly disagree. </seg>
<seg id="20"> charles di bona, analyst with market research firm sanford c. bernstein, says that it is still too early to talk about google shaking windows' dominate position. </seg>
<seg id="21"> reporter handbook: is google shaking up microsoft's landscape? </seg>
<seg id="22"> hui zhengyi </seg>
<seg id="23"> without doubt, the computer has become a necessity in modern man's life and work. </seg>
<seg id="24"> but while everybody has become familiar with operating computers, only a small portion of people understand the working principles behind a computer. </seg>
<seg id="25"> just like with an "idiot" camera, if the interface is friendly and the software is convenient and quick to use, the vast majority of "newbies" can find their way around the black box that is a computer. </seg>
<seg id="26"> for this reason, the software originally installed by the pc manufacturer more often than not determines the usage habits of most consumers. </seg>
<seg id="27"> indeed, it was through this measure that microsoft took firm hold of the market for pc operating systems. </seg>
<seg id="28"> now, microsoft's new rival, google, also intends to use this method to take a piece of the pie. </seg>
<seg id="29"> in regards to this, a well-known organization in the taiwanese economic media recently made an interesting analogy. </seg>
<seg id="30"> "dell, hp and other computer manufacturers are starting to treat the computers they produce as supermarket shelves and they are charging 'top shelf fees' to software companies. </seg>
<seg id="31"> the winning bidder can cause its software to appear in the 'crucial ten minutes' after the user turns on the new computer and thereby induce the consumer to use their product. </seg>
<seg id="32"> this type of fee method is like the top-shelve fees charged by supermarkets to food companies." </seg>
<seg id="33"> without doubt, this phenomenon indicates that microsoft's control is being shaken. </seg>
<seg id="34"> microsoft's managers have warned bill gates, saying that if google starts paying money to pc manufacturers in order to have computers shipped with google software installed, then microsoft's position as overlord will ultimately be threatened. </seg>
<seg id="35"> whatever the final outcome, microsoft's easy days safely perched at the top of the ladder might become history. </seg>
<seg id="36"> after all, keeping a market is much more difficult than creating a market</seg>
