<hl>
<seg id="1"> <headline> xu zhiyong: a letter to li qun, party secretary of the linyi cpc municipal committee </seg>
</hl>
<poster>
<seg id="2"> <poster>  fa bulin </seg>
</poster>
<seg id="3"> sender: sunnypku (sunny), </seg>
<seg id="4"> mail list: square </seg>
<seg id="5"> title: xu zhiyong: a letter to li qun, party secretary of the linyi cpc municipal committee--by using hooligan tactics, you will harm yourselves too. </seg>
<seg id="6"> website of origin: yjrg.net (wed feb 8 13:56:14 2006), current website (yjrg.net) </seg>
<seg id="7"> as of yesterday, the government of linyi, of which you are the leader, has held chen guangcheng under illegal house arrest for 165 days. </seg>
<seg id="8"> you have joined with hooligan and gangland elements to illegally imprison a law-abiding citizen who is completely blind. </seg>
<seg id="9"> you have cut his home's telephone line and installed mobile phone interrupters in his courtyard. </seg>
<seg id="10"> on several occasions, you have also beat him or members of his family. </seg>
<seg id="11"> your barbaric acts have transgressed the lowest limits of civilized society. </seg>
<seg id="12"> at the beginning of october, 2005, you employed hooligan gangland tactics to beat the lawyer li fangping and myself, but we have been patient and have always done our best to understand the difficult situation you are in. for a period of time, we even tolerated that you had placed chen guangcheng under house arrest. </seg>
<seg id="13"> but 165 days have gone by and you still haven't restrained yourselves. on the contrary, you have intensified your efforts. </seg>
<seg id="14"> you have dispatched large contingents of police and thugs to harass the villagers. </seg>
<seg id="15"> you have continued to arrest and beat villagers. </seg>
<seg id="16"> you have gone too far! </seg>
<seg id="17"> today, as you continue to organize underworld thugs to surround chen guangcheng, we clearly warn you that thuggish underworld tactics will in turn come back to hurt you. </seg>
<seg id="18"> you need to rethink this affair from its beginning. </seg>
<seg id="19"> province wide, linyi ranks last in planned parenthood. </seg>
<seg id="20"> as municipal party secretary, it is understandable that you are somewhat anxious. </seg>
<seg id="21"> but you are mistaken in your belief that the people of linyi are of such low upbringing that it is necessary to use violence and coercion to implement state laws and policies. </seg>
<seg id="22"> if citizens do not act in concert with the actions of government, in the end whose fault is it? </seg>
<seg id="23"> is it because the citizens are of low upbringing or is it because for a long time the government has engaged in so much lying and deception that its public credibility is too low? </seg>
<seg id="24"> assuming that ten years ago the same type of actions by government didn't seem so outrageous, don't you feel that, in 2005, when chinese society has made clear progress and human-rights guarantees have been written into the constitution, your savage acts seem ludicrous? </seg>
<seg id="25"> think about it for a moment. how is it that only you people in linyi dare to act this way? </seg>
<seg id="26"> how is it that only you people in linyi are unable to enforce the law using democratic and legal methods? </seg>
<seg id="27"> in the wake of the reports by chen guangcheng and other courageous citizens regarding the savage enforcement of laws, the brave intercedence by teng biao and other legal personnel to protect the rights of citizens, as well as the conclusions drawn from the investigation by the state family planning commission, the city of linyi could have, in good faith, offered an explanation and reached a compromise with the public. </seg>
<seg id="28"> when all is said and done, family planning is a difficult problem that is specific to china. </seg>
<seg id="29"> likewise, we can all empathize with the difficult situation you are in. </seg>
<seg id="30"> but you nevertheless went on to employ outrageous measures--arresting chen guangcheng and bringing him back from beijing to be held prisoner, then attempting to have him found guilty of illegally revealing state secrets. </seg>
<seg id="31"> don't you find it quite ludicrous to accuse a blind man from a poor mountain village of that crime? </seg>
<seg id="32"> actually, if you had truly corrected your errors, if you had acted correctly, would you fear the criticism of a blind man? </seg>
<seg id="33"> did you have to send several dozen people to keep watch over him twenty-four hours a day and, flustered and exasperated, even have him accused of a crime? </seg>
<seg id="34"> on october 4, 2005, attorney li fangping and i arrived in dong shigu village. we put forth a very clear position in the hope of resolving the conflict. </seg>
<seg id="35"> we suggested that we could first talk with your officials to see what thoughts and demands you had. </seg>
<seg id="36"> we took the initiative of suggesting that we could help you persuade chen guangcheng that there are some things he should not say. </seg>
<seg id="37"> we hoped that you would not treat a blind person in such a manner. there should be concessions from both sides. </seg>
<seg id="38"> but your decision-makers clung obstinately to their course. furthermore, you unexpectedly came up with a "careful plan"--beating us and detaining us illegally. </seg>
<seg id="39"> do you think you can intimidate us in this way? </seg>
<seg id="40"> we haven't done anything illegal, </seg>
<seg id="41"> so we have nothing to fear. </seg>
<seg id="42"> although the rule of law in china may not be perfect, but neither is it at the point of lawlessness. </seg>
<seg id="43"> if you think you can use thuggish tactics to intimidate us, then you have greatly underestimated our determination and perseverance. </seg>
<seg id="44"> if we want, there are many of us with abundant legal justifications to go to linyi or visit chen guangcheng. </seg>
<seg id="45"> you can beat a lawyer or an academic once, twice, three times, and each time there will be widespread attention and reporting. </seg>
<seg id="46"> do you really dare to beat us ten times? </seg>
<seg id="47"> isn't it your official position that you are so worried about? </seg>
<seg id="48"> if the beatings actually result in somebody being injured, will your position be so assured? </seg>
<seg id="49"> you don't listen to our rational advice, but instead resort to low-class ruffian tactics. don't you find this very foolish and also very dangerous? </seg>
<seg id="50"> i want to make it clear to you that there is a large group of outstanding citizens in china that are devoted to the just adherence to the rule of law. </seg>
<seg id="51"> we are not afraid of ruffian criminal elements. </seg>
<seg id="52"> we will not tolerate the brazen trampling of the lowest limits of human civilization. </seg>
<seg id="53"> if you go too far, we will confidently and calmly step forward, group after group, to welcome your clubs until the moment that you shrink back. </seg>
<seg id="54"> you should understand clearly that the use of hooligan tactics is in no way a good thing for you. </seg>
<seg id="55"> don't think that after you retreat behind the scenes you will be able to break off your involvement with those local ruffians that beat villagers. </seg>
<seg id="56"> finally, we also want to remind you that you should treat chen guangcheng well. </seg>
<seg id="57"> blind since childhood, he graduated from collegial studies in chinese medicine and then taught himself law and english. in the past, he brought legal action against the beijing subway company in order to fight for the rights of blind people and also had running water installed for the villagers. he has become known near and far as "attorney chen". </seg>
<seg id="58"> you have unexpectedly mobilized unabashed flunkies to spread rumors and slander him on the internet and have attempted to have him sentenced with the crime of illegally providing secrets to foreigners. don't you think that in doing so you have gone too far? </seg>
<seg id="59"> your house arrest of chen guangcheng is illegal. it is also dangerous for you yourself. </seg>
<seg id="60"> at first, you were fully capable of releasing him. </seg>
<seg id="61"> inasmuch as the savage enforcement of the law had already ceased, he could criticize all he wanted, but how long would he go on? </seg>
<seg id="62"> but you are now steadily denigrating your own image. </seg>
<seg id="63"> until cheng guangcheng obtains his freedom, you will not have a day of peace. </seg>
<seg id="64"> you have persecuted him enough. </seg>
<seg id="65"> if you try to have him convicted of a crime or attempt to use further thuggish tactics, we will not fold our arms and stand by. </seg>
<seg id="66"> xu zhiyong, citizen, february 8, 2006 </seg>
</DOC>
